tnamization--as Richard Nixon termed it in 1969--and the end of South Vietnam signals more than an example of flawed American military strategy, but a larger allegory of power, providing cover for U.S. imperial losses while denoting the inability of the (South) Vietnamese and other colonized nations to become independent, modern liberal subjects. Bui argues that the collapse of South Vietnam under Vietnamization complicates the already difficult memory of the Vietnam War, pushing for a critical understanding of South Vietnamese agency beyond their status as the war’s ultimate “losers.” Examining the lasting impact of Cold War military policy and culture upon the “Vietnamized” afterlife of war, this book weaves questions of national identity, sovereignty, and self-determination to consider the generative possibilities of theorizing South Vietnam as an incomplete, ongoing search for political and personal freedom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aRefugeeszVietnam (Republic). 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975xRefugees. 0aVietnamese Americans. 0aVietnamesezUnited StatesxHistoriography. 7aHISTORY / Military / Vietnam War.2bisacsh  aAimee Phan.  aAllies.  aAmerican Syndrome.  aClinton.  aCold War.  aHo Chi Minh City.  aLittle Saigon.  aNixon.  aOrange County.  aOrderly Departure Program.  aSaigon.  aSouth Vietnam.  aViet Kieu.  aVietnam Syndrome.  aVietnam War Center and Archive.  aVietnam memoir.  aVietnamization.  aanti-communism.  aarchival others.  adismemberment.  aglobalization.  amemory work.  amilitarized freedoms.  amilitary.  aoral histories.  aoral history.  apolitical prisoners.  areeducation.  arefugee.  arememberment.  asecond generation.  aurbanization.  awar trauma.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Co